11:11 November eleventh was chosen as the time for the armistice.  Nov 11 was already on the Church calendar as St. Martin's day.  It was celebrated as the end of the harvest season and the beginning of winter.  In a grim twist of irony it was also a day of slaughtering livestock for winter provisions.

In parts of Germany, 11:11 Nov 11 also marks the start of Carnaval season which peaks on Shrove Tuesday the day before the start of Lent. (I learned this last part while reading the Carnaval or Fasching  section of The Magic Mountain.)

@Al  in Pittsburgh
Armistice Day AKA Remembrance Day has an interesting life in literature.  In Dorothy L. Sayers's brilliantly named _The  Unpleasantness at the Bellona Club_, Remembrance Day's importance and traditions are beautifully shown and play a crucial role in solving the mystery. And they have an ongoing role in Louise Penny's mystery series.
Every year, it is an intense demonstration of the power of silence, the power of stopping, knowing that the ground is as important as the figure.

